<Base title="Privacy Policy" description="How Cardo handles your data: locally, transparently, and — where the internet is involved — with your explicit consent.">
  <h1>Privacy Policy</h1>
  <p class="muted">Last updated: July 17, 2026 · Responsible: Leif Hollatz (see <a href="mailto:kontakt@heike-wagner-hollatz.de">contact</a>)</p>

  <section class="card block">
    <h2>The short version</h2>
    <p>
      Cardo is a local-first application: <strong>your data lives on your device</strong>, in a
      local database and in files you own. There is no Cardo account, no Cardo cloud, no tracking,
      no analytics, and no advertising — neither in the app nor on this website (which also sets
      no cookies). We, the developers, <strong>never see your content</strong>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card block">
    <h2>What stays on your device</h2>
    <p>
      Everything you create: to-dos, notes, calendar entries, habits, health logs, finances,
      assistant conversations, settings, themes. Cardo stores this in a local SQLite database and
      in a notes folder on your machine. Nothing of it is transmitted anywhere unless you
      explicitly enable a feature listed below.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card block">
    <h2>When the app talks to the internet</h2>
    <p>Every tool that contacts the internet carries a yellow privacy light in the app and explains what it sends <em>before</em> you activate it. The complete list:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Update check</strong> — Cardo periodically asks our update server (GitHub) whether a new version exists. Transmitted: the app's version number. Configurable in Settings → Updates.</li>
      <li><strong>Inbox &amp; polls (opt-in)</strong> — fetches announcements/polls from our server. Votes are anonymous: only a one-way hash of a random installation id is sent, never anything about you.</li>
      <li><strong>Weather</strong> — sends the city name you type to open-meteo.com to fetch the forecast.</li>
      <li><strong>Currency converter</strong> — sends a three-letter currency code to open.er-api.com, at most once a day.</li>
      <li><strong>RSS reader</strong> — contacts exactly the feed URLs you add, nobody else.</li>
      <li><strong>AI model downloads</strong> — downloads model files from huggingface.co when you set up the local assistant. The models then run entirely on your device.</li>
      <li><strong>Claude assistant (opt-in)</strong> — if you connect your own Anthropic subscription, your assistant messages and workspace files are sent to Anthropic. Cardo shows a consent dialog first; Anthropic's privacy policy applies to that processing.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card block">
    <h2>Sync (opt-in) and end-to-end encryption</h2>
    <p>
      Sync is off by default. If you enable it, Cardo encrypts your data <strong>on your device</strong>
      (XChaCha20-Poly1305) with a key that only you hold — it is stored in your operating system's
      keychain and never transmitted. The storage you choose (see below) only ever receives
      unreadable encrypted blocks. Losing every device and the key means the synced data is
      unrecoverable — by design, because nobody but you can decrypt it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card block">
    <h2>Cardo's use of Google Drive (opt-in sync transport)</h2>
    <p>
      If you choose Google Drive as your sync transport and sign in with your Google account,
      Cardo requests exactly one permission: <code>drive.appdata</code> — access to its own hidden
      application-data folder in <em>your</em> Drive. Concretely:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Cardo <strong>cannot see, read, or change any of your Drive files</strong>. It can only create, read, and delete files inside its own hidden app folder.</li>
      <li>The only data written there are your <strong>end-to-end encrypted sync blocks</strong>. Google (and anyone else with access to the storage) cannot decrypt them.</li>
      <li>Google user data is used <strong>solely to provide the sync feature you enabled</strong>. It is never sold, never used for advertising, never transferred to third parties, and never used to train AI models.</li>
      <li>Your Google sign-in token is stored in your operating system's keychain, on your device only. Disconnecting in Settings → Sync deletes it; you can additionally revoke Cardo's access at <a href="https://myaccount.google.com/permissions" rel="noopener">myaccount.google.com/permissions</a>, and delete the app folder's contents from there.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Cardo's use and transfer of information received from Google APIs adheres to the
      <a href="https://developers.google.com/terms/api-services-user-data-policy" rel="noopener">Google API Services User Data Policy</a>,
      including the Limited Use requirements.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card block">
    <h2>This website</h2>
    <p>
      Hosted on GitHub Pages (GitHub, Inc.). GitHub may log technical access data (IP address,
      user agent) to operate the service; see
      <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/site-policy/privacy-policies/github-general-privacy-statement" rel="noopener">GitHub's privacy statement</a>.
      The site itself sets no cookies and runs no analytics. The forum lives in GitHub
      Discussions and follows GitHub's terms.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card block">
    <h2>Your rights &amp; contact</h2>
    <p>
      Since your data is stored locally on your device, you exercise access, correction, and
      deletion directly: Settings → Data &amp; backup exports everything; deleting the app (and,
      if used, the Drive app folder) removes it. For any privacy question, contact
      <a href="mailto:kontakt@heike-wagner-hollatz.de">kontakt@heike-wagner-hollatz.de</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

